# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tigergraph
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:tigergraph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:tigergraph/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:tigergraph/gsql-ref-intro] The **GSQL™** software program is the TigerGraph comprehensive environment for designing graph schemas, loading and managing data to build a graph, and querying the graph to perform data analysis.
[src:tigergraph/gsql-ref-intro] TigerGraph now also supports **OpenCypher** and the pattern matching portion of **GQL**, within the same execution engine.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:tigergraph/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:tigergraph/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:tigergraph/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
